Dear yakkers

Hard on the heels of my first post in a long time, I'm also curious
about something that happened during a brief appearance interpreting
in court for a young (24 year old) defendant a week ago.

My court experience is typically in commercial litigation, with
fairly sophisticated plaintiffs and defendants. This was a criminal
matter of a very unsophisticated nature (we'll just leave it at that,
I think....) The situation was what is called a 'mention' here in
Australia, which I think is probably the American equivalent of an
arraignment.

When the judge said 'how do you plead', and I used the word 答弁　to
interpret him, the accused said 「答弁って」?

So, did I use the wrong word, or is your average young Japanese so
unfamiliar with the legal process? The laddie didn't seem to get 有罪
or 無罪, either.

Regards
Heather Glass
