Me too, because what happened is that when the accused said 「答弁っ
て？」I translated that back to the judge, who then re-phrased with
something  like &quot;Have you anything to say about the charge?&quot;, and the
accused said 「気持ちですか」, then with the judge's 'yes' went on to
explain 「全面的に私が悪いと認めています」. When I interpreted that,
the judge announced he would record a plea of guilty.

So, the process was served, but there was obviously either a
perception or an expectation gap between the Australian judge and the
Japanese accused.

If I followed your guide,  Mike, and invited the accused to 'say
something' about the charges, there's a very real possibility that
with the wrong judge in the Australian context, the accused would cop
a reprimand for not just answering the question (he didn't have legal
representation, by the way, so he was travelling blind), or worse if
he kept trying to 'say something', be placed in contempt of court.

The position of a mention in the Australian legal context may be like
起訴認否手続 in Japan I think. In the Australian mention, the accused
is read the charges and given the opportunity to have them dealt with
by the judge there and then by pleading guilty, or have it go to a
full hearing with legal representation if necessary, by pleading not
guilty.

Heather Glass
