The temptation is to think of 「自分の罪を認めますか？」 as meaning
&quot;Do you acknowledge your crime?&quot;  The English wording presumes
that you have committed a crime, and the only question is whether you
admit having committed it, or are instead denying it.
I do not know whether this Japanese wording has the same connotations.

Similarly with the equation of 事実 = fact.
If something is a fact, then by definition of the word &quot;fact&quot;, it really happened.
But in Japanese legal language it appears that 事実 does not
always mean &quot;fact&quot;.  It sometimes merely stands for a &quot;that &lt;statement&gt;&quot; clause
and might best be translated as as &quot;claim&quot;, &quot;allegation&quot;, &quot;accusation&quot;, etc.

Guidance from the more knowledgeable is welcome.
-- Mark Spahn  (West Seneca, NY)
