I don't think there is any presumption of guilt in the simple question of how one pleads at arraignment.

A presumption of guilt puts the burden of proof on the defense to prove that the accused is innocent. Conversely, a presumption of innocence puts the burden of proof on the prosecution to prove their guilt.

Regardless of this matter of presumption, I think that a very important consideration when asking the defendant how they plead is that they are made very aware of the gravity of answering the question in the affirmative. They must know very clearly that they are admitting their guilt, something that may prove very difficult to retract later. They are not simply acknowledging that they understand the charges or such.

Posing the question in a very clear manner such as that above could avoid subsequent complications such as a defendant not realizing until too late that they had inadvertently plead guilty.

