I can't speak for the Japanese system but the Australian system the initial
appearance is simply to decide whether the matter is contested or not. If
the defendant pleads guilty they are admitting the charge, as set out by the
prosecution. If the person denies the charge they enter a plea of not
guilty.

Not guilty does not mean &quot;I did nothing&quot; - it means &quot;I am not guilty of the
charge as set out&quot;. For example the charge of shoplifting requires that the
prosecution prove that (a) the defendant not only took items from a store
without paying for them, but that (b) at the time of doing so had no such
intention to pay for them.

When it comes time to enter a plea, whether the defendant's case is that
they absentmindedly picked an item up and walked out with paying for it, or
a case of complete mistaken identity, the initial plea is simply &quot;not
guilty&quot;, because neither situation constitutes guilt under the charge in
question.

The exact words used in putting this to a defendant  may vary - &quot;Do you
admit this charge?&quot;, &quot;What do you say to this charge?&quot; but the objective is
the same - the prosecution has charged the defendant with a crime, and the
defendant must say whether they admit the charge or not.

To someone not familiar with the situation they might want to say &quot;Yeah, I
took it, but I didn't mean to...&quot; - but the court is not interested in the
nitty gritty at this preliminary stage - the court just wants to know if you
admit the charge as set out by the prosecution. If you took the item but
meant to pay for it then you do not admit the charge of shoplifting and
should just say &quot;Not guilty&quot;

Pleading guilty to spending too much time in front of the computer

