Jim Lockhart's remarks about &quot;proof&quot; versus &quot;evidence&quot;
are a spur to try to clarify the difference between them. My attempt:
evidence (of an assertion) = something that supports the assertion
proof (of an assertion) = evidence sufficient to compel belief in the assertion.
(And while we're at it, faith = belief in the absence of proof.)

In pondering Alan Siegrist's remarks, it seems that there are
two classes of verbs that deal with statements, that is,
verbs that when expressed in Japanese can be used with
the quotative particle と :
(1) &quot;know&quot;-like verbs:  know, admit, concede, acknowledge,
own up to, prove, establish
(2) &quot;believe&quot;-like verbs:  believe, think, say, assert, claim, declare,
proclaim, announce.

With a &quot;know&quot;-like verb, the statement must be true.
In order for the statement &quot;I know that my Redeemer liveth&quot;
to be true, one's Redeemer must actually live.
One cannot know a false statement; the meaning of &quot;know&quot;
does not allow such a possibility.
But with a &quot;believe&quot;-like verb, the statement could be false.
&quot;I believe that my Redeemer liveth&quot; can be true even if
one's Redeemer does not live.

My expectation (vulnerable to statistical refutation by a survey)
is that there is little or nor disagreement among native speakers
about which statement verbs are &quot;know&quot;-like and which are
&quot;believe&quot;-like.  Probably a few centuries ago some philosopher
clarified the distinction between these two classes of statement
verbs with far greater clarity than this poor attempt of mine.

So is 認める a &quot;know&quot;-like verb (=admit, acknowledge),
or is it a &quot;believe&quot;-like verb (=declare (one's guilt or innocence))?
My understanding is that it is a &quot;know&quot;-like verb,
but maybe I'm wrong.

Mark Spahn @ taking a stab at concept clarification
